\subsection{Error Level Analysis (ELA)}

ELA is a forensic preprocessing technique that reveals JPEG compression inconsistencies. The core idea is that authentic regions of an image compress uniformly, while tampered regions~--- composited from different sources or saved at different quality levels~--- show inconsistent compression residuals.

\subsubsection{Mathematical Formulation}

Given an input image $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 3}$ and a JPEG quality level $Q \in \{1, \ldots, 100\}$, the ELA map is computed as:
\begin{equation}
    \text{ELA}_Q(\mathbf{X}) = \left| \mathbf{X} - \text{JPEG}_Q(\mathbf{X}) \right| \cdot s
    \label{eq:ela}
\end{equation}
where $\text{JPEG}_Q(\cdot)$ denotes JPEG re-compression at quality $Q$, and $s$ is a brightness scaling factor such that the maximum channel difference maps to 255:
\begin{equation}
    s = \frac{255}{\max_{i,j,c} \left| X_{i,j,c} - \text{JPEG}_Q(\mathbf{X})_{i,j,c} \right| + \epsilon}
\end{equation}
with $\epsilon = 10^{-8}$ for numerical stability.

\subsubsection{Multi-Quality RGB ELA (Best Variant)}

Instead of a single quality level, the best configuration uses three quality levels, each producing an RGB ELA map (3 channels). These are stacked to form a 9-channel input:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{X}_{\text{MQ-ELA}} = \left[ \text{ELA}_{75}(\mathbf{X}) \,\|\, \text{ELA}_{85}(\mathbf{X}) \,\|\, \text{ELA}_{95}(\mathbf{X}) \right] \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 9}
\end{equation}
where $\|$ denotes channel-wise concatenation.

Each quality level captures different forensic information:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Multi-Quality ELA Channel Statistics (from P.15 training set)}
\label{tab:ela_stats}
\begin{tabular}{l c c l}
\toprule
\textbf{Quality} & \textbf{Mean} & \textbf{Std} & \textbf{Sensitivity} \\
\midrule
Q=75 (aggressive) & 0.0684 & 0.0656 & Strong manipulations \\
Q=85 (balanced) & 0.0605 & 0.0604 & Medium edits \\
Q=95 (gentle) & 0.0402 & 0.0471 & Subtle changes \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The three channels carry meaningfully different statistics~--- lower $Q$ produces larger residuals, confirming they provide distinct, non-redundant forensic information.

